# ğŸ§® Day 3 - LeetCode 18: 4Sum
  You may return the answer in **any order**, but the solution set must not contain duplicate quadruplets.

ğŸ”— **Problem Link:** [LeetCode 18 - 4Sum](https://leetcode.com/problems/4sum/)

---

## ğŸ§  Approach
1. **Sorting:** First, sort the array to easily skip duplicates and use two-pointer technique.  
2. **Two loops + Two pointers:**  
   - Fix the first two elements (`i` and `j`).
   - Use two pointers (`left`, `right`) to find the remaining two numbers.
3. **Avoid duplicates:** Skip repeated numbers to ensure unique quadruplets.

â± **Time Complexity:** O(nÂ³)  
ğŸ“¦ **Space Complexity:** O(1)

---

## ğŸ’» Code Implementation
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> fourSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        int n=nums.size();
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(i>0 && nums[i]==nums[i-1]) continue;
            for(int j=i+1;j<n;){
                int p=j+1,q=n-1;
                while(p<q){
                long sum= (long)nums[i] + (long)nums[j] + (long)nums[p] + (long)nums[q];
                if(sum>target){
                    q--;
                }
                else if(sum<target){
                    p++;
                }
                else{
                    ans.push_back({nums[i],nums[j],nums[p],nums[q]});
                    p++;
                    q--;
                    while(p<q && nums[p]==nums[p-1]) p++;

                }
                }
                j++;
                  while(j<n && nums[j]==nums[j-1]) j++;
            }
          

        }
        return ans;
    }
};
